{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01RvhpQmxVJAoKvrktzzGaHn","type":"tool_result","content":"21:* daemon / GitHub issue and PR automation\n22-* a large binary-level conformance suite\n23-\n24:That picture is visible in `src/workflow/{orchestrator,quick_dev_orchestrator}.rs`, `src/project/*`, `src/backend/*`, `src/prd/*`, `src/daemon/*`, and `src/validate/*` (all under `multibackend-orchestration/`).\n25-\n26-The rewrite lives in **`ralph-burning-rewrite/`**, with a new workspace root **`.ralph-burning/`** and a fully new storage model. The legacy codebase should be used as a **behavior and domain reference only**. The rewrite should not preserve or read/write legacy `.ralph` state, legacy markdown artifact formats, legacy loop directories, or legacy git checkpoint encodings.\n27-\n28-The recommended target is a **Rust modular monolith** with explicit bounded contexts and selective hexagonal architecture around real side-effect boundaries. The most important design changes are:\n29-\n30-* replace “standard orchestrator vs quick-dev orchestrator” with a **shared workflow engine**\n31-* make **flow presets** first-class and fixed per project\n32-* support exactly these built-in flow presets in v1:\n33-\n34-  * `standard`\n--\n50:* **Automation Runtime**\n51-* **Conformance Specification**\n52-\n53-The biggest risks are architectural, not technical:\n54-\n55-* rebuilding giant orchestrators under new names\n56-* over-generalizing into a workflow DSL too early\n57-* letting stage markdown remain a protocol instead of rendered output\n58-* allowing flow-specific state to leak back into the project model\n59:* under-specifying operator-facing behavior like `history`, `tail`, `rollback`, `flow show`, and daemon routing\n60-\n61-The right rewrite is decisive: a greenfield modular monolith, typed workflow kernel, built-in flow presets, mandatory structured stage payloads across all supported backends, and a new conformance suite that captures desired behavior rather than legacy file formats.\n62-\n63-# Current System Summary\n64-\n65-## Core purpose\n66-\n67-Today the repo implements a local-first AI software-delivery orchestrator that coordinates multiple AI backends to perform engineering work inside a repository. It persists state locally, integrates with git, produces readable artifacts, and exposes operator controls for running, inspecting, resuming, validating, rolling back, generating PRDs, and automating GitHub-driven work.\n68-\n69-## Main user/operator workflows in the current system\n--\n103:* interactive PRD issue workflow in `src/daemon/interactive_prd.rs`\n104-\n105:### Automation / daemon workflows\n106-\n107:The daemon is a real subsystem, not a thin wrapper. It includes:\n108-\n109-* polling and claiming GitHub issues\n110-* worktree management\n111:* task dispatch\n112-* draft PR lifecycle\n113-* rebase handling\n114-* interactive PRD issue advancement\n115-\n116:That behavior is concentrated in `src/daemon/{runtime,tasks,github,worktree,rebase_agent,interactive_prd}.rs`.\n117-\n118-## Runtime shape\n119-\n120-The current runtime is one Rust binary with multiple operating modes:\n121-\n122-* direct CLI commands\n123:* long-running daemon\n124-* PRD pipeline execution\n125-* validate/conformance execution\n126-\n127-It depends on:\n128-\n129-* local workspace/project state under `.ralph/`\n130-* local git repository/worktrees\n131-* external backend CLIs\n132-* optional tmux\n133:* GitHub / `gh` integration for daemon paths\n134-\n135-## Main moving parts\n136-\n137-### `src/backend/`\n138-\n139-Contains backend spec parsing, backend selection, model injection, subprocess execution, tmux integration, output normalization, and backend-specific quirks.\n140-\n141-### `src/workflow/`\n142-\n143-Contains the main orchestration logic and the separate quick-dev orchestration logic.\n--\n157:### `src/daemon/`\n158-\n159:Contains issue routing, task lifecycle, worktree behavior, PR watcher behavior, rebase, and interactive PRD.\n160-\n161-### `src/validate/`\n162-\n163-Contains a broad executable behavior suite and is the strongest evidence of current external behavior.\n164-\n165-## Important current strengths\n166-\n167-* The repo already captures real product behavior, not just internal architecture ideas.\n168-* The conformance suite is broad and valuable.\n169-* The system has meaningful operator recovery concepts: status, history, tail, resume, rollback.\n--\n171:* PRD and daemon are real capabilities, not side scripts.\n172-* Readable artifacts are genuinely useful for debugging and audit.\n173-\n174-## Important current weaknesses\n175-\n176-* The biggest weakness is the split between the standard/full workflow and quick-dev. That makes adding new flows expensive and invasive.\n177-* `ProjectState` is carrying flow-specific state instead of hosting a clean, generic run model.\n178-* The standard orchestrator mixes policy with filesystem, git, backend, template, and parsing mechanics.","is_error":false}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_0172JmZWncG6Pf7nVUtxXudN","session_id":"ac8d6a2a-5f6d-4606-9741-7014e6740f51","uuid":"7f5041e2-768f-4816-b1a8-759a15cdec1f"}
