{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01NqAMbvgjG32speFZUfi2hQ","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→---\n     2→artifact: spec\n     3→loop: 10\n     4→project: ralph-burning-rewrite\n     5→backend: codex(gpt-5.4-xhigh)\n     6→role: planner\n     7→created_at: 2026-03-12T19:38:14Z\n     8→---\n     9→\n    10→I’m reviewing the current rewrite workspace, loop artifacts, and git history to determine what is already implemented and what the next missing slice should be. First I’ll inspect `prompt.md`, the completed loop specs, and the current code/test surface so the next feature is grounded in what actually exists.\n    11→The workspace is the rewrite repo under `ralph-burning-rewrite/`; loop 9 is the latest completed checkpoint. I didn’t get `prompt.md` from the first pass, so I’m narrowing into the rewrite project and the loop/spec artifacts that define current scope and completed behavior.\n    12→I’ve confirmed the planning state lives under `.ralph/projects/ralph-burning-rewrite/`, with loop specs through 009 approved. Next I’m checking the actual prompt, the latest spec, and the code/test surface for `quick_dev`, `requirements`, `daemon`, and `conformance` so I can avoid proposing a slice that is already in place.\n    13→The shared engine is already generalized for all flow semantics, including `quick_dev`; the only hard block I’ve found there is the CLI guard that still rejects `quick_dev`. In contrast, `requirements`, `daemon`, and `conformance` are still command stubs with empty context modules, so I’m checking whether the roadmap and existing tests make `quick_dev` or `requirements drafting` the next real gap.\n    14→The roadmap pattern is consistent: loops 1 through 9 map directly to roadmap items 1 through 9, and there’s no loop 10 implementation in git history. I’m pulling the legacy PRD/reference materials now so the next spec can be detailed without accidentally inheriting old storage or protocol decisions.\n    15→I found one architectural coupling that matters for the next slice: `agent_execution` currently hardcodes `workflow_composition::StageContract` and the project-flow `StageId`. Requirements drafting will need structured contracts too, so the spec needs to generalize that interface instead of smuggling requirements stages into the project workflow enum.\n    16→# Feature: Requirements Drafting and Project Seed Handoff\n    17→\n    18→## Description\n    19→Loops 1 through 9 already delivered the rewrite foundation: workspace init and flow discovery, stage contracts and renderers, effective config and active project resolution, canonical project/run storage and queries, agent execution, standard-flow orchestration, retry/resume semantics, completion rounds and amendments, and docs/CI flow execution. Git checkpoint history stops at loop 9 planning, and the entire `requirements` bounded context plus all four `requirements` CLI commands are still stubs at `HEAD`. The next missing roadmap slice is a canonical requirements-run workflow under `.ralph-burning/requirements/` that can draft requirements from an idea, pause for clarifying answers when needed, and emit a durable project-seed handoff without auto-creating a project or touching legacy `.ralph` PRD state.\n    20→\n    21→## Acceptance Criteria\n    22→- [ ] Introduce a `RequirementsRun` state model persisted at `.ralph-burning/requirements/<run-id>/run.json` with, at minimum, `run_id`, `idea`, `mode` (`draft` or `quick`), `status` (`drafting`, `awaiting_answers`, `completed`, `failed`), `question_round`, `latest_question_set_id`, `latest_draft_id`, `latest_review_id`, `latest_seed_id`, `created_at`, `updated_at`, and `status_summary`.\n    23→- [ ] Each requirements run also persists `journal.ndjson`, `answers.toml`, `answers.json`, `history/payloads/*`, `history/artifacts/*`, `seed/project.json`, `seed/prompt.md`, and `runtime/{logs,backend}/*` under `.ralph-burning/requirements/<run-id>/`.\n    24→- [ ] `requirements show <run-id>` derives its read model from `run.json` and `journal.ndjson`, not by scanning artifacts, and prints the run ID, mode, status, question round, last failure summary if present, pending question count, recommended flow, and the seed prompt path when complete.\n    25→- [ ] Define structured contracts and deterministic renderers for four requirements-stage outputs: `question_set`, `requirements_draft`, `requirements_review`, and `project_seed`.\n    26→- [ ] Requirements contract validation follows the same invariant as project stages: schema validation occurs before any state mutation, domain validation occurs after schema validation and before transition commit, and rendered Markdown is never parsed for control flow.\n    27→- [ ] `question_set` payloads include stable question IDs, prompt text, rationale, `required` flag, and optional suggested defaults; those IDs are the only keys accepted in `answers.toml` and persisted `answers.json`.\n    28→- [ ] `requirements_draft` payloads include a problem summary, goals, non-goals, constraints, acceptance criteria, risks or open questions, and a recommended flow constrained to the built-in presets only: `standard`, `quick_dev`, `docs_change`, or `ci_improvement`.\n    29→- [ ] `project_seed` payloads include a recommended project `id`, project `name`, built-in `flow`, a final `prompt.md` body, and a short handoff summary suitable for manual `project create --prompt`.\n    30→- [ ] `requirements draft --idea \"<text>\"` creates a new run, durably records the idea, invokes question generation, and either transitions to `awaiting_answers` after committing the question payload/artifact plus an editable `answers.toml` template, or continues directly into draft/review/seed generation when no questions are required.\n    31→- [ ] `requirements quick --idea \"<text>\"` creates a new run in `quick` mode, skips question generation entirely, and executes draft -> review -> seed generation in one command using the same persistence and validation rules.\n    32→- [ ] `requirements answer <run-id>` is valid for runs in `awaiting_answers` and for failed runs whose latest durable boundary is a committed question set; it opens `<run-dir>/answers.toml` in `$EDITOR`, validates that every required question has a non-empty answer, persists `answers.json`, and resumes from the answers boundary instead of creating a new run.\n    33→- [ ] If `$EDITOR` fails or exits non-zero during `requirements answer`, the run state, journal, and previously accepted answers remain unchanged.\n    34→- [ ] Requirements drafting reuses `agent_execution`, but `agent_execution` must be generalized from workflow-only `StageContract` usage to a domain-neutral structured-contract interface so requirements contracts do not have to be added to the project workflow `StageId` enum.\n    35→- [ ] Planner defaults drive question generation, drafting, and project-seed generation; reviewer defaults drive requirements review; existing workspace default backend/model resolution and raw-output persistence rules continue to apply.\n    36→- [ ] Review outcomes have distinct semantics: `approved` allows seed generation and completion; `conditionally_approved` still completes but records follow-ups in canonical seed metadata and the rendered handoff summary; `request_changes` and `rejected` fail the run after the review payload/artifact are durably committed and before any seed files become visible.\n    37→- [ ] State invariants for partial failure are explicit: if the question payload/artifact pair fails to persist, the run must not transition to `awaiting_answers` and no partial question/template files may remain visible.\n    38→- [ ] State invariants for partial failure are explicit: if answer validation fails, `answers.json` is not replaced, no draft/review/seed stage runs, and the run remains at the same committed question boundary.\n    39→- [ ] State invariants for partial failure are explicit: if the draft or review payload/artifact pair fails to persist, the corresponding journal success event is not appended and no downstream stage begins.\n    40→- [ ] State invariants for partial failure are explicit: if `seed/project.json` is written but `seed/prompt.md` fails, both seed outputs are removed, the run remains non-completed, and only the already committed draft/review history survives.\n    41→- [ ] Completed requirements runs are immutable, failed runs retain the latest committed question set, answers, draft, and review artifacts, and `question_round` is monotonic across repeated answer cycles.\n    42→- [ ] `requirements show <run-id>` prints a suggested `ralph-burning project create --id ... --name ... --flow ... --prompt <seed/prompt.md>` command assembled from `seed/project.json` and `seed/prompt.md`.\n    43→- [ ] This loop does not auto-create, mutate, select, or delete projects; project handoff is durable seed output only, leaving `project create` as an explicit user action.\n    44→- [ ] Public behavior is covered by new Gherkin scenarios for: draft requiring answers, draft with no questions, quick-mode happy path, editor failure, answer validation failure, conditional approval handoff, review request_changes failure, and seed-write rollback.\n    45→- [ ] Existing workspace, project, and run behavior remains unchanged, including the current quick_dev run-execution deferral outside the `requirements` command surface.\n    46→\n    47→## Files to Modify/Create\n    48→- `src/contexts/requirements_drafting/mod.rs` - replace the placeholder with module exports and public entrypoints for the requirements lifecycle\n    49→- `src/contexts/requirements_drafting/model.rs` - add requirements run IDs, status enums, journal event types, pointers to latest payloads, and seed metadata\n    50→- `src/contexts/requirements_drafting/contracts.rs` - define domain-neutral contracts for `question_set`, `requirements_draft`, `requirements_review`, and `project_seed`\n    51→- `src/contexts/requirements_drafting/renderers.rs` - render deterministic `questions.md`, `requirements.md`, `review.md`, and seed handoff artifacts\n    52→- `src/contexts/requirements_drafting/service.rs` - orchestrate `draft`, `quick`, `show`, and `answer`, including answer-template validation and seed rollback rules\n    53→- `src/contexts/agent_execution/model.rs` - generalize invocation metadata away from workflow-only `StageContract` coupling\n    54→- `src/contexts/agent_execution/service.rs` - support domain-neutral contract evaluation while preserving existing workflow behavior\n    55→- `src/contexts/workflow_composition/contracts.rs` - adapt existing workflow stage contracts to the generalized agent-execution contract interface\n    56→- `src/adapters/fs.rs` - add filesystem stores for requirements runs, journals, answer files, payload/artifact history, runtime diagnostics, and atomic seed-pair writes\n    57→- `src/adapters/stub_backend.rs` - add deterministic requirements-stage payloads for tests\n    58→- `src/cli/requirements.rs` - implement all four requirements commands and the editor-driven answer flow\n    59→- `src/shared/error.rs` - add invalid requirements state, answer validation, and seed persistence error variants\n    60→- `tests/conformance/features/requirements_drafting.feature` - add public requirements-drafting scenarios\n    61→- `tests/unit/requirements_drafting_test.rs` - add domain and service tests for the requirements state machine and failure invariants\n    62→- `tests/cli.rs` - add end-to-end CLI coverage for `requirements draft`, `requirements quick`, `requirements show`, and `requirements answer`\n    63→\n    64→## Dependencies\n    65→- Requires: Loop 9 (Docs Change and CI Improvement Flow Execution)\n    66→- Blocks: Loop 11 (Daemon routing, tasks, leases, watchers, rebase, and interactive requirements path)\n    67→\n    68→---\n    69→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_01RZX7TKqEYTqZzxLDs7ifaD","session_id":"ac8d6a2a-5f6d-4