ntics for start, resume, remediation, completion-round restarts, amendment drain, and prompt-review pause; keep standard wrappers for compatibility.\n    20→3. Update CLI `run start` / `run resume` to allow `docs_change` and `ci_improvement`, keeping `quick_dev` rejected.\n    21→4. Extend unit tests and CLI tests for docs/CI flows, add a dedicated `flow_semantics_test.rs`, and add the requested Gherkin feature files.\n    22→5. Run the project test/build command, fix failures, then write the required implementation-notes markdown file.\n    23→I’m editing the flow-composition layer first so the engine can consume one semantic descriptor instead of hardcoded standard-stage IDs.\n    24→I’m refactoring the engine entrypoints now. The goal is to land the generic API first, then replace the remaining hardcoded stage semantics inside the loop.\n    25→I’ve replaced the main restart/pause/drain logic with flow-semantic lookups. I’m cleaning up the resume helpers and the remaining stage-plan utilities now, which is where most of the hardcoded `planning`/`implementation` strings still live.\n    26→I’m switching the CLI over to the generic engine next. That change is small, but it’s the gate that exposes docs/CI flows while still rejecting `quick_dev`.\n    27→I’m expanding test helpers before adding the new cases so the docs/CI flow tests can reuse the same workspace/project setup as the standard-flow tests.\n    28→I’m adding the non-standard engine tests in the same integration-style unit file so they exercise the real FS stores, journal, payload/artifact persistence, and resume path the same way the standard tests do.\n    29→I’m adding a dedicated flow-semantics test file now, separate from the engine tests, so the structural mapping stays explicit and easy to review when future presets get added.\n    30→I’m updating the CLI integration tests now. These are the user-facing regression gate for `run start`, so I’m keeping the changes narrow: docs/CI should succeed, `quick_dev` should still fail.\n    31→The existing Gherkin still describes docs/CI as unsupported. I’m correcting those scenarios too, otherwise the new feature files would conflict with the old source-of-truth docs.\n    32→The code paths are wired. I’m running the full Rust test suite now; anything that broke from the engine refactor or the new API surface gets fixed before I close this out.\n    33→`cargo` isn’t on the default PATH in this shell. I’m locating the toolchain and rerunning the test suite with the explicit binary path.\n    34→The suite is compiling now. I’m waiting on the first pass to surface any type errors from the engine refactor before I touch anything else.\n    35→Compilation reached the link step; the remaining blocker is environmental, not Rust code: the shell doesn’t have `cc` on PATH. I’m locating a usable linker and rerunning the suite with that PATH injected.\n    36→The one failing test exposed a real contract interaction: the canned rejected payload for validation has no follow-up items, so contract evaluation rejects it as a domain error before the engine can classify it as a QA/review failure. I’m fixing the test payload to represent a valid rejected validation result.\n    37→The full suite is green. I’m writing the required implementation-notes markdown file now, using the verified outcomes and one ambiguity I preserved intentionally.\n    38→# Implementation Notes\n    39→\n    40→## Decisions Made\n    41→- Added `FlowSemantics` and `stage_plan_for_flow(...)` in [mod.rs](/root/new-ralph-burning/ralph-burning-rewrite/src/contexts/workflow_composition/mod.rs) so built-in flows map structural roles instead of hardcoded standard-stage IDs.\n    42→- Generalized the orchestration engine in [engine.rs](/root/new-ralph-burning/ralph-burning-rewrite/src/contexts/workflow_composition/engine.rs) to `execute_run` / `resume_run`, preserved `execute_standard_run` / `resume_standard_run` as wrappers, and switched remediation, completion-round restart, amendment drain, prompt-review pause, and resume reconstruction to flow-semantics lookups.\n    43→- Updated CLI handling in [run.rs](/root/new-ralph-burning/ralph-burning-rewrite/src/cli/run.rs) so `docs_change` and `ci_improvement` run on the shared engine while `quick_dev` still returns `UnsupportedFlow`.\n    44→- Added coverage in [workflow_engine_test.rs](/root/new-ralph-burning/ralph-burning-rewrite/tests/unit/workflow_engine_test.rs), [flow_semantics_test.rs](/root/new-ralph-burning/ralph-burning-rewrite/tests/unit/flow_semantics_test.rs), [cli.rs](/root/new-ralph-burning/ralph-burning-rewrite/tests/cli.rs), and the new feature files [run_start_docs_change.feature](/root/new-ralph-burning/ralph-burning-rewrite/tests/conformance/features/run_start_docs_change.feature), [run_start_ci_improvement.feature](/root/new-ralph-burning/ralph-burning-rewrite/tests/conformance/features/run_start_ci_improvement.feature), and [run_resume_non_standard.feature](/root/new-ralph-burning/ralph-burning-rewrite/tests/conformance/features/run_resume_non_standard.feature). I also corrected the outdated docs/CI support text in [run_start_standard.feature](/root/new-ralph-burning/ralph-burning-rewrite/tests/conformance/features/run_start_standard.feature).\n    45→\n    46→## Spec Deviations\n    47→- Non-late `ConditionallyApproved` outcomes still do not persist follow-ups in `run.json`. The current canonical model only has the durable amendment queue, and the spec also says docs/CI flows should not queue durable amendments, so I preserved the existing non-blocking behavior instead of inventing a new snapshot field in this loop.\n    48→\n    49→## Testing\n    50→- Verified with `cargo test` and fixed the only failing case uncovered during the run. Because this shell did not expose `cargo` or `cc` on `PATH`, I ran the suite with explicit Nix toolchain/linker paths.\n    51→\n    52→---\n    53→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_01RZX7TKqEYTqZzxLDs7ifaD","session_id":"ac8d6a2